</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The internal thoracic (IT) nodal basin is a first-echelon drainage pathway in the breast, accounting for up to a quarter of its lymphatic drainage, primarily from the deep structures of the breast. The presence of internal thoracic node (ITN) metastases upstages the breast cancer (BC) patient to a minimum of clinical stage III disease. Medial tumors, deep tumors, young age, axillary nodal metastases, tumors of a high nuclear grade, lymphovascular invasion, and triple-negative hormone receptor status are predisposing factors for ITN metastases from primary BC. It has been observed that medial tumors carry a worse prognosis than lateral tumors when all other factors are equal, indicating that understaging of ITN has a significant impact on patient outcomes. Despite the established prognostic significance of IT adenopathy in BC, this nodal basin is not routinely staged due to the difficulty in accessing it and due to the controversy regarding its management. Since the initial ITN studies in the 1960s, improvement in imaging techniques and the availability of minimally invasive biopsy techniques have fueled renewed interest in ITNs and their clinical significance in BC. Radiologists who image and diagnose BC can offer more accurate staging assessments by consistently evaluating the IT nodal chain in the BC patient. In this article, the authors discuss current knowledge of the ITNs in BC and review ITN anatomy. The imaging appearance of pathologic ITNs using various modalities, potential mimics of IT adenopathy, and image-guided sampling techniques are described. A succinct discussion of the clinical management of ITN-positive BC and its challenges is also included.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup> RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160166">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160166">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig1.jpeg" height="1790" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Illustration shows normal anatomy of the <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in relation to surrounding structures. <i>ICS =</i> intercostal space, <i>ITV</i> = internal thoracic vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig2a.jpeg" height="1359" width="1767" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. <b>(a)</b> Panoramic ultrasonographic (US) image of the parasternal region in a normal patient. <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s, if visible, would be seen in the intercostal spaces. <b>(b)</b> Transverse power Doppler flow US image displays a normal 5-mm <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) within the second intercostal space adjacent to the <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig2b.jpeg" height="1359" width="1583" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. <b>(a)</b> Panoramic ultrasonographic (US) image of the parasternal region in a normal patient. <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s, if visible, would be seen in the intercostal spaces. <b>(b)</b> Transverse power Doppler flow US image displays a normal 5-mm <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) within the second intercostal space adjacent to the <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig3a.jpeg" height="965" width="1714" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 3a</span>. Node in the first intercostal space in a 39-year-old patient with invasive ductal carcinoma, lymphovascular invasion, and associated axillary lymphadenopathy. <b>(a)</b> Panoramic parasternal US image shows a 1.3 × 0.6-cm node (arrow) in the first intercostal space that revealed metastatic carcinoma at fine-needle aspiration biopsy (<abbr title="fine-needle aspiration biopsy">FNAB</abbr>). <b>(b)</b> Longitudinal gray-scale US image shows the same node (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig3b.jpeg" height="965" width="1436" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 3b</span>. Node in the first intercostal space in a 39-year-old patient with invasive ductal carcinoma, lymphovascular invasion, and associated axillary lymphadenopathy. <b>(a)</b> Panoramic parasternal US image shows a 1.3 × 0.6-cm node (arrow) in the first intercostal space that revealed metastatic carcinoma at fine-needle aspiration biopsy (<abbr title="fine-needle aspiration biopsy">FNAB</abbr>). <b>(b)</b> Longitudinal gray-scale US image shows the same node (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig4.jpeg" height="1702" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 4</span>. Transverse power Doppler US image shows a 1.9-cm enlarged <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) in a 49-year-old woman with invasive ductal <abbr title="breast cancer">BC</abbr>. The node is adjacent to the <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> vessels of the first intercostal space.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig5.jpeg" height="979" width="1842" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 5</span>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in a 49-year-old patient with invasive ductal <abbr title="breast cancer">BC</abbr> shows an enhancing soft-tissue mass (arrow) in the left parasternal region, consistent with <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> lymphadenopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig6a.jpeg" height="979" width="1708" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 6a</span>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and postcontrast T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show a right breast mass (long arrow) and an adjacent enhancing right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (short arrow) in a 41-year-old woman with poorly differentiated invasive ductal carcinoma. The adjacent enhancing right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (short arrow) is at the upper limit of normal in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig6b.jpeg" height="1015" width="1993" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 6b</span>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and postcontrast T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show a right breast mass (long arrow) and an adjacent enhancing right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (short arrow) in a 41-year-old woman with poorly differentiated invasive ductal carcinoma. The adjacent enhancing right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (short arrow) is at the upper limit of normal in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig7.jpeg" height="1015" width="1755" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 7</span>. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows two adjacent left breast masses (yellow arrows) and a 1.6-cm enhancing right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (white arrow) in a 54-year-old patient with invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig8a.jpeg" height="1977" width="1099" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Coronal maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT images in axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> planes show an enlarged <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (long arrow in <b>a–c</b>) in a 49-year-old woman with recurrent invasive ductal carcinoma. An adjacent preaortic lymph node (short arrow in <b>a–c</b>) is also intensely <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig8b.jpeg" height="1553" width="1854" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Coronal maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT images in axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> planes show an enlarged <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (long arrow in <b>a–c</b>) in a 49-year-old woman with recurrent invasive ductal carcinoma. An adjacent preaortic lymph node (short arrow in <b>a–c</b>) is also intensely <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig8c.jpeg" height="1553" width="1696" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Coronal maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT images in axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> planes show an enlarged <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (long arrow in <b>a–c</b>) in a 49-year-old woman with recurrent invasive ductal carcinoma. An adjacent preaortic lymph node (short arrow in <b>a–c</b>) is also intensely <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig8d.jpeg" height="1979" width="1351" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Coronal maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT images in axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> planes show an enlarged <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (long arrow in <b>a–c</b>) in a 49-year-old woman with recurrent invasive ductal carcinoma. An adjacent preaortic lymph node (short arrow in <b>a–c</b>) is also intensely <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig9a.jpeg" height="1850" width="1210" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. <b>(a)</b> Lymphoscintigram after peritumoral tracer injection in a 43-year-old woman with immediate-grade ductal carcinoma in situ shows drainage to two left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (long arrows) and a left axillary node (short arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> single photon emission computed tomography (SPECT)/CT images help confirm drainage (arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) to the <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig9b.jpeg" height="1850" width="1440" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. <b>(a)</b> Lymphoscintigram after peritumoral tracer injection in a 43-year-old woman with immediate-grade ductal carcinoma in situ shows drainage to two left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (long arrows) and a left axillary node (short arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> single photon emission computed tomography (SPECT)/CT images help confirm drainage (arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) to the <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig9c.jpeg" height="1191" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. <b>(a)</b> Lymphoscintigram after peritumoral tracer injection in a 43-year-old woman with immediate-grade ductal carcinoma in situ shows drainage to two left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (long arrows) and a left axillary node (short arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> single photon emission computed tomography (SPECT)/CT images help confirm drainage (arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) to the <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig10.jpeg" height="1816" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Illustration shows peritumoral injection of radiotracer with drainage to <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> sentinel nodes (in pink).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig11a.jpeg" height="1301" width="1099" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Coronal MIP image <b>(a)</b> and fused axial PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show an <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid 0.8-cm right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) in an 88-year-old patient with large B-cell lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig11b.jpeg" height="1301" width="1851" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Coronal MIP image <b>(a)</b> and fused axial PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show an <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid 0.8-cm right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) in an 88-year-old patient with large B-cell lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig12a.jpeg" height="1021" width="1716" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enlarged left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) in a 61-year-old patient with metastatic carcinoid. <b>(b)</b> Fused axial PET/CT image shows an <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) in a 66-year-old patient with widely metastatic ovarian cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig12b.jpeg" height="1021" width="1634" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enlarged left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) in a 61-year-old patient with metastatic carcinoid. <b>(b)</b> Fused axial PET/CT image shows an <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) in a 66-year-old patient with widely metastatic ovarian cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig13.jpeg" height="1224" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Axial postcontrast CT image shows an anterior mediastinal mass (arrows) in a patient with thymoma. The mass extends from the parasternal region to the great vessels. In the appropriate clinical context, a thymoma might mimic IT lymphadenopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig14a.jpeg" height="1353" width="1158" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in a 61-year-old woman with remote invasive ductal BC and a history of a ruptured silicone implant. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images show mildly enlarged enhancing bilateral <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a 1.5-cm enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image shows multiple shotty <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in the bilateral intercostal spaces and an enlarged <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> in the right first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Fused axial PET/CT image shows that the enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) is moderately <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid. Given that silicone granulomas can be <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid, the findings are equivocal. The size of the node is considered suspicious. <b>(e)</b> Transverse parasternal US image shows hyperechoic silicone lymphadenopathy in multiple intercostal spaces (arrows = second space adenopathy). These findings are benign, and a biopsy was avoided.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig14b.jpeg" height="1352" width="1196" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in a 61-year-old woman with remote invasive ductal BC and a history of a ruptured silicone implant. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images show mildly enlarged enhancing bilateral <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a 1.5-cm enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image shows multiple shotty <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in the bilateral intercostal spaces and an enlarged <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> in the right first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Fused axial PET/CT image shows that the enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) is moderately <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid. Given that silicone granulomas can be <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid, the findings are equivocal. The size of the node is considered suspicious. <b>(e)</b> Transverse parasternal US image shows hyperechoic silicone lymphadenopathy in multiple intercostal spaces (arrows = second space adenopathy). These findings are benign, and a biopsy was avoided.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig14c.jpeg" height="1353" width="1346" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in a 61-year-old woman with remote invasive ductal BC and a history of a ruptured silicone implant. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images show mildly enlarged enhancing bilateral <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a 1.5-cm enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image shows multiple shotty <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in the bilateral intercostal spaces and an enlarged <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> in the right first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Fused axial PET/CT image shows that the enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) is moderately <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid. Given that silicone granulomas can be <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid, the findings are equivocal. The size of the node is considered suspicious. <b>(e)</b> Transverse parasternal US image shows hyperechoic silicone lymphadenopathy in multiple intercostal spaces (arrows = second space adenopathy). These findings are benign, and a biopsy was avoided.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig14d.jpeg" height="1182" width="1781" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in a 61-year-old woman with remote invasive ductal BC and a history of a ruptured silicone implant. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images show mildly enlarged enhancing bilateral <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a 1.5-cm enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image shows multiple shotty <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in the bilateral intercostal spaces and an enlarged <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> in the right first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Fused axial PET/CT image shows that the enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) is moderately <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid. Given that silicone granulomas can be <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid, the findings are equivocal. The size of the node is considered suspicious. <b>(e)</b> Transverse parasternal US image shows hyperechoic silicone lymphadenopathy in multiple intercostal spaces (arrows = second space adenopathy). These findings are benign, and a biopsy was avoided.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig14e.jpeg" height="1182" width="1369" aria-labelledby="fig14e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14e</span>. <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in a 61-year-old woman with remote invasive ductal BC and a history of a ruptured silicone implant. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images show mildly enlarged enhancing bilateral <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a 1.5-cm enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image shows multiple shotty <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s in the bilateral intercostal spaces and an enlarged <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> in the right first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Fused axial PET/CT image shows that the enlarged right <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow) is moderately <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid. Given that silicone granulomas can be <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid, the findings are equivocal. The size of the node is considered suspicious. <b>(e)</b> Transverse parasternal US image shows hyperechoic silicone lymphadenopathy in multiple intercostal spaces (arrows = second space adenopathy). These findings are benign, and a biopsy was avoided.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig14e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig15.jpeg" height="1082" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Fused axial staging PET/CT image shows <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid mediastinal, hilar, and IT adenopathy in a 56-year-old patient with invasive ductal carcinoma. Transbronchial biopsy of multiple mediastinal and hilar nodes was negative for carcinoma but demonstrated nonnecrotic granulomas. Follow-up PET/CT after 6 months (not shown) revealed stable <abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr>-avid adenopathy, consistent with a granulomatous process.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig16a.jpeg" height="902" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. <abbr title="short τ inversion recovery">STIR</abbr> MR image <b>(a)</b> and PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 54-year-old woman with treated recurrent mixed invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted <abbr title="short τ inversion recovery">STIR</abbr> MR image shows a single enlarged left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow). Biopsy revealed benign lymphoid tissue. <b>(b)</b> PET/CT image from a 4-month follow-up shows mediastinal, hilar, and <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy. A second biopsy of a different <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> revealed benign lymphoid tissue, which was thought to be concordant with a benign inflammatory process. The patient is being followed conservatively and was well at 6-month follow-up examination.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig16b.jpeg" height="1220" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. <abbr title="short τ inversion recovery">STIR</abbr> MR image <b>(a)</b> and PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 54-year-old woman with treated recurrent mixed invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted <abbr title="short τ inversion recovery">STIR</abbr> MR image shows a single enlarged left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrow). Biopsy revealed benign lymphoid tissue. <b>(b)</b> PET/CT image from a 4-month follow-up shows mediastinal, hilar, and <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy. A second biopsy of a different <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> revealed benign lymphoid tissue, which was thought to be concordant with a benign inflammatory process. The patient is being followed conservatively and was well at 6-month follow-up examination.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig17.jpeg" height="1562" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. US-guided <abbr title="fine-needle aspiration biopsy">FNAB</abbr> of an enlarged left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> (arrowheads) in a 49-year-old woman with recurrent invasive ductal <abbr>BC.</abbr> Pathologic analysis showed metastatic <abbr title="breast cancer">BC</abbr> and necrosis. The patient was treated with chemotherapy followed by radiation therapy to the left chest wall and <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain. Arrows = needle shaft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig18.jpeg" height="1424" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Axial nonenhanced CT image acquired during CT-guided biopsy of a suspicious left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> in an 83-year-old woman. The <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr> was detected shortly after mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma. Pathologic analysis demonstrated metastatic carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig19a.jpeg" height="1108" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Recurrent invasive ductal carcinoma in a 64-year-old patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows left IT adenopathy (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT images from a three-dimensional (3D) conformal radiation treatment plan to the left chest wall and left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s. Dose to the heart is a concern for patients with left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy, but it is minimized with careful planning, including integration of treatment in breath hold, which displaces the heart from the high-dose region.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig19b.jpeg" height="2280" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Recurrent invasive ductal carcinoma in a 64-year-old patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows left IT adenopathy (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT images from a three-dimensional (3D) conformal radiation treatment plan to the left chest wall and left <abbr title="internal thoracic node">ITN</abbr>s. Dose to the heart is a concern for patients with left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy, but it is minimized with careful planning, including integration of treatment in breath hold, which displaces the heart from the high-dose region.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig20a.jpeg" height="979" width="1823" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Pathologic T1c cancer of the lower inner quadrant of the left breast in a 49-year-old patient. Axillary sentinel node biopsy was negative, but there was biopsy-proven involvement of the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> nodal chain. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest shows <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy (arrow). Radiation therapy to the left breast and <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain draining using deep-inspiration breath hold was initiated after chemotherapy. <b>(b–d)</b> Three-dimensional illustrations show an intensity-modulated radiation therapy boost delivered to the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain following completion of a 3D conformal radiation plan to 50 Gy. Images show a frontal view <b>(b)</b>, CT scout images with graphic overlays of the radiation plan <b>(c)</b>, and an axial view <b>(d)</b> of the radiation therapy boost.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig20b.jpeg" height="1130" width="1810" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Pathologic T1c cancer of the lower inner quadrant of the left breast in a 49-year-old patient. Axillary sentinel node biopsy was negative, but there was biopsy-proven involvement of the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> nodal chain. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest shows <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy (arrow). Radiation therapy to the left breast and <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain draining using deep-inspiration breath hold was initiated after chemotherapy. <b>(b–d)</b> Three-dimensional illustrations show an intensity-modulated radiation therapy boost delivered to the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain following completion of a 3D conformal radiation plan to 50 Gy. Images show a frontal view <b>(b)</b>, CT scout images with graphic overlays of the radiation plan <b>(c)</b>, and an axial view <b>(d)</b> of the radiation therapy boost.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig20c.jpeg" height="979" width="1927" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Pathologic T1c cancer of the lower inner quadrant of the left breast in a 49-year-old patient. Axillary sentinel node biopsy was negative, but there was biopsy-proven involvement of the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> nodal chain. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest shows <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy (arrow). Radiation therapy to the left breast and <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain draining using deep-inspiration breath hold was initiated after chemotherapy. <b>(b–d)</b> Three-dimensional illustrations show an intensity-modulated radiation therapy boost delivered to the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain following completion of a 3D conformal radiation plan to 50 Gy. Images show a frontal view <b>(b)</b>, CT scout images with graphic overlays of the radiation plan <b>(c)</b>, and an axial view <b>(d)</b> of the radiation therapy boost.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160166/asset/images/large/rg.2017160166.fig20d.jpeg" height="1130" width="1540" aria-labelledby="fig20d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20d</span>. Pathologic T1c cancer of the lower inner quadrant of the left breast in a 49-year-old patient. Axillary sentinel node biopsy was negative, but there was biopsy-proven involvement of the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> nodal chain. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest shows <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> adenopathy (arrow). Radiation therapy to the left breast and <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain draining using deep-inspiration breath hold was initiated after chemotherapy. <b>(b–d)</b> Three-dimensional illustrations show an intensity-modulated radiation therapy boost delivered to the left <abbr title="internal thoracic">IT</abbr> chain following completion of a 3D conformal radiation plan to 50 Gy. Images show a frontal view <b>(b)</b>, CT scout images with graphic overlays of the radiation plan <b>(c)</b>, and an axial view <b>(d)</b> of the radiation therapy boost.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160166&amp;id=fig20d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kawase K, Gayed IW, Hunt KK, et al. Use of lymphoscintigraphy defines lymphatic drainage patterns before sentinel lymph node biopsy for breast cancer. <em>J Am Coll Surg</em> 2006;203(1):64–72.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jamcollsurg.2006.03.015">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16798488/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Use+of+lymphoscintigraphy+defines+lymphatic+drainage+patterns+before+sentinel+lymph+node+biopsy+for+breast+cancer&amp;author=K+Kawase&amp;author=IW+Gayed&amp;author=KK+Hunt&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=J+Am+Coll+Surg&amp;pages=64-72&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.jamcollsurg.2006.03.015&amp;pmid=16798488">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Suami H, Pan WR, Mann GB, Taylor GI. The lymphatic anatomy of the breast and its implications for sentinel lymph node biopsy: a human cadaver study. <em>Ann Surg Oncol</em> 2008;15(3):863–871.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1245/s10434-007-9709-9">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18043970/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+lymphatic+anatomy+of+the+breast+and+its+implications+for+sentinel+lymph+node+biopsy%3A+a+human+cadaver+study&amp;author=H+Suami&amp;author=WR+Pan&amp;author=GB+Mann&amp;author=GI+Taylor&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=Ann+Surg+Oncol&amp;pages=863-871&amp;doi=10.1245%2Fs10434-007-9709-9&amp;pmid=18043970">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Madsen EV, Aalders KC, van der Heiden-van der Loo M, et al. Prognostic significance of tumor-positive internal mammary sentinel lymph nodes in breast cancer: a multicenter cohort study. <em>Ann Surg Oncol</em> 2015;22(13):4254–4262.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1245/s10434-015-4535-y">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25808100/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Prognostic+significance+of+tumor-positive+internal+mammary+sentinel+lymph+nodes+in+breast+cancer%3A+a+multicenter+cohort+study&amp;author=EV+Madsen&amp;author=KC+Aalders&amp;author=M+van+der+Heiden-van+der+Loo&amp;publication_year=2015&amp;journal=Ann+Surg+Oncol&amp;pages=4254-4262&amp;doi=10.1245%2Fs10434-015-4535-y&amp;pmid=25808100">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div cla